title: rinnegan
body:
The Rinnegan, as depicted in [[Naruto]], is reputed as the most exalted eyes amongst the Three Great Dōjutsu, the others being the Byakugan and the Sharingan. They are characterised by light purple or red sclerae and irides with a ripple-pattern that spreads over the eyeball that are sometimes marked with tomoe.

Both of [[Uchiha Madara]]'s eyes eventually become this. Upon his impending death, his eyes are transplanted into a young [[Nagato (naruto)|]], who later exposes them via the use of the [[pain (Naruto)|Six Paths of Pain]]. After Nagato's demise and his unmasking, [[Uchiha Obito]]'s left eye socket is shown to have one of Madara's original Rinnegan implanted in it, and [[Uchiha Sasuke]]'s Eternal Mangekyou Sharingan is evolved into a powered up Rinnegan as he is visited by the Sage of the Six Paths while in near death.

title: gulf_war
body:
A [[war]] that took place in the Persian Gulf region from August 2, 1990, to February 28, 1991. The war was triggered by Ba'athist [[Iraq]]'s invasion and annexation of [[Kuwait]], which was seen as a threat to the security of the neighboring countries and the global oil supply.

A coalition of 34 countries, led by the [[United States]], formed to oppose [[Saddam Hussein]]'s Iraq's aggression and to liberate Kuwait. The coalition included several Arab countries, such as [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Egypt]], and [[Syria]], as well as Western countries such as the [[United Kingdom]], [[France]], and [[Canada]]. The coalition launched a massive military operation to drive Iraqi forces out of Kuwait, known as Operation Desert Storm.

The war began with a series of air strikes on Iraqi military targets, followed by a ground offensive. The coalition forces achieved a quick and decisive victory, and Kuwait was liberated from Iraqi occupation. The war lasted for less than six months, with the majority of the fighting taking place between January and February 1991.

The Gulf War had significant political, economic, and social consequences. It marked a turning point in the global politics of the Middle East, as well as in the use of military force to resolve international disputes. The war also had a severe impact on the civilian population, with thousands of Kuwaiti civilians and Iraqi civilians being killed or displaced.

The war also led to the imposition of sanctions on Iraq, which remained in place for over a decade, and had a significant impact on the country's economy and population. Additionally, the Gulf War led to the deployment of US military forces in the region, which has had a lasting impact on the politics and security of the Middle East.

h4. See Also

title: toad_(animal)
body:
An amphibious four-legged [[animal]]. 
[b]Not to be confused with[/b] [[frog]]. Unlike frogs, the physical differences of toads are rough, dry skin, warts on body, stockier body, crests under eyes and mostly come in dull colouring. Toads prefer to crawl and jump on shorter distance compared to frogs. 
Toads are found on every continent, excluding [[Antarctica]]. They prefer to inhabit humid, moist areas like [[wetland]]s, [[pond]]s, or [[lake]]s. Both frogs and toads do croaking vocalization, lay eggs, grow up from [[tadpole]]s, and feed on small animals which are mainly [[bug]]s. Toad tadpoles look chunkier than frog ones.

For the character in the Mario series, see [[Toad (Mario)]].

body:
[b]Midori no Hibi[/b], also known as [b]Midori Days[/b], is an eight-volume fantasy manga series written and drawn by [[Inoue Kazurou]], later adapted into a 13-episode anime.

The central characters are [[Sawamura Seiji]], a tough but lonely delinquent known for beating people up with his "Devil's Right Hand," and [[Kasugano Midori]], a shy girl who (apparently due to her unrequited love for Seiji) wakes up one morning in a miniature-sized version of her real body, attached to Seiji's arm where his right hand was.

Adding to the complications are numerous characters with designs (usually romantic, but not always) on Seiji, the original Midori, or the Midori on Seiji's arm.  Primary among these is [[Ayase Takako]], a strait-laced classmate of Seiji's who initially despises him as a delinquent, but after he rescues her from a gang, develops a deep secret crush on him and starts a series of increasingly outlandish schemes to win his affection.

title: 506th_parachute_infantry_regiment_(us_army)
body:
One of three parachute regiments that made up the [[101st Airborne]] during [[World War II]], the [b]506th[/b] saw combat service from the D-Day invasion to the end of the war in Europe, and continues as part of the 101st Airmobile Division today. The regiment was made famous thanks in part to the television series [[Band of Brothers]], which focused on the regiment's E Company ("Easy") during WW2.

Depictions of the regiment will almost invariably be of its appearance in World War II, with the "Screaming Eagle" patch of the 101st Airborne worn on the left shoulder. The major visual indicator of the 506th is the "spade" insignia (from a deck of cards) on the helmet, which was done before the Normandy landings to allow for easy identification. (The division's other regiments - two parachute and glider - used the other three card suits on theirs.)

h4.See also
* [[Band of Brothers]].
* [[101st Airborne]].

title: satire
body:
A form of humorous social commentary/media meant to display criticism. Satiric posts often involves ironic uses of exaggerated and/or metaphorical imagery to highlight certain flaws of the subject.

Please note that just because it's funny, it does not mean it's satire. On the same token, just because it's a funny picture concerning a [[politician]], it is NOT satire.

Also, please note the difference between [[satire]] and [[parody]]. Before you add the satire tag, ask yourself "Is this picture trying to prove a point?"

h4.See also

* Related tags on Pixiv: 風刺 ('satire') or '時事 ('topical issue' ~ rare case)'

title: pokemon_vega
body:
A [[Pokemon|Pokémon]] ROM hack built upon the foundation of [[Pokemon FRLG|Pokémon Fire Red]], originally released in 2010. It is the sequel to [[Pokemon Altair and Sirius|Pokémon Altair & Sirius]]. As of 2016, the hack has had an English-language port, with translation work having been conducted on the Nuzlocke Forums.

Pokémon Vega broke new ground in 2010 by introducing the physical/special split to GBA Pokémon and utilizing a number of then-new Pokémon from [[Pokemon BW|Generation V]]. It expanded upon the many [[Fakemon|custom Pokémon]] introduced in its prequels and added a substantial number of new ones, adding up to a full Pokédex of 386.

The game takes place in a brand-new, custom region named Tohoak, a land completely covered in snow. The story references many events from the [[Pokemon (anime)|Pokémon anime movies]] on top of its own core conflict, in which the player must take down Team Dark Hole and their ambition to use the Meteoric Pokémon for nefarious ends.

title: zao_(cruiser)
body:
A fictional name for Japan's Tier 10 heavy cruiser in [i][[World of Warships]][/i]. Named for Mount Zaou (蔵王山), in keeping with the IJN naming convention that heavy cruisers were named after mountains in Japan. Zao is known for having guns with very good muzzle velocity, nicknamed "railguns" by players. 

h4. History
It is actually debatable as to whether or not plans for [i]Zaou[/i] actually existed due to the destruction of sensitive information by the IJN prior to surrender. What is known is that a triple 203 mm gun mount, never actually mounted on any Japanese CA, was considered for eight ships planned under the Sixth Naval Armaments Program but no other information has survived. Certain postwar sources such as [i]Japanese Cruisers of the Pacific War[/i] and [i]Uncompleted Fleet Plan - 1917~1950[/i], from where the [i]Zaou[/i] design was based from, are informed guesses. These sources also give the class name as the [i]Unzen[/i]-class, of which [i]Zaou[/i] was supposed to be the [b]third[/b] member. 

h4. See also
* [[Unzen (Azur Lane)|]]

title: shirasaya
body:
A [[katana]] blade fitted with a plain wooden grip and sheath ([i]saya[/i]) that, when fitted together, completely conceal the blade and resemble a [[bokken]]. This configuration was intended to be used for storage or transportation of blades, not combat, since in addition to the decorative furniture characteristic of katana, a blade in [i]shirasaya[/i] also lacks a hand guard ([i]tsuba[/i]), making it unsafe to wield. Despite this fact, it's not uncommon for [i]shirasaya[/i] blades to be depicted as weapons in active use.

The signature sword carried by Zatoichi, the blind swordsman and eponymous protagonist of the [[Zatoichi]] films, resembles a  [i]shirasaya[/i]; however, the blade is straight and the purpose of the plain wooden furniture is not to protect it in storage, but rather to disguise it as a blind man's cane.

title: hosokawa_gracia
body:
[b]Akechi Tama[/b], usually referred to as Hosokawa Garasha (細川ガラシャ), (1563 – 25 August 1600) was a member of the aristocratic Akechi family from the Sengoku period. Gracia is best known for her role in the [[Battle of Sekigahara]]; she was considered to be a political hostage to the Western army led by [[Ishida Mitsunari]]. She reneged on committing suicide ([[seppuku]]) because of her Catholic faith, breaking the code of conduct imposed on women of the samurai class.

She was the daughter of [[Akechi Mitsuhide]] and [[Tsumaki Hiroko]], the wife of [[Hosokawa Tadaoki]], and a convert to Catholicism. As the last notable survivor of the Akechi clan, the clan that planned and executed the assassination of [[Oda Nobunaga]], the first "Great Unifier" of Japan, Gracia's death impacted both armies. The incident did much damage to Ishida's reputation, which greatly reduced his chances of recruiting more allies, some of whom were also secretly Christians. Gracia's actions consequently led to Mitsunari's defeat; triggering the events that would lead to the formation of the [[Tokugawa Shogunate]].

title: king_(tekken)
body:
[b]King[/b] is a famous [[luchador]] from [[Mexico]] that appears in the [[Tekken]] 3D fighting game series. 

There are actually two Kings in the series, both of whom wore a [[animal head|jaguar mask]] in matches.

The character was inspired by both legendary Japanese pro wrestler [[Tiger Mask (character)|]], as well as Mexican wrestler [i]Fray Tormenta[/i], a Catholic [[priest]] who became a masked wrestler in order to support an orphanage. 

King does not speak, per se. Instead, he makes growls and snarls in the manner of a [[jaguar]], which are translated into English subtitles at the bottom of the screen. Interestingly, other characters do not have a problem understanding King, and converse with him as though he was speaking naturally.

body:
An American single-shot, muzzle-loading [[40mm grenade|40mm]] [[underbarrel grenade launcher]]. It was designed to replace the [[M79]], which was a stand-alone weapon. The under-barrel design gave soldiers the advantage of having quicker switch of both [[rifle]] and [[grenade launcher]], making them more adaptable in combat. The M203 was originally designed designed for the [[M16]] and [[M4 Carbine]] but can be fitted to many other rifles without modification.

title: byerley_turk_(umamusume)
body:
In [i][[Umamusume]][/i], the Byerley Turk refers both to one of the Three Goddesses of the [i]Umamusume[/i] universe as well as a training AI based on her, who is one of the hosts of the Grand Masters scenario. She represents "Discipline" and is represented by the color yellow.

A [[horse girl]], she has short brown and black two-toned hair as well as purple eyes. She wears a yellow military-style outfit and has a scar across her left eye. Overall, she somewhat resembles [[Symboli Rudolf (umamusume)|]] (and not by coincidence, as described below). She has a crown-like accessory on [b]her right ear[/b].

She is based on the Byerley Turk, one of the foundation sires of the Thoroughbred breed of horses. His umamusume's military theme is based on the fact that the Byerley Turk was originally a war horse. Through Herod, he is the sire-line ancestor of about 4% of all Thoroughbreds. In the context of [i]Umamusume[/i], he is the real-life ancestor of only 6 characters: Those who are part of Partholon's sire-line ([[Symboli Rudolf (umamusume)|]], [[Tokai Teio (umamusume)|]], [[Tsurumaru Tsuyoshi (umamusume)|]], [[Samson Big (umamusume)|]] and [[Mejiro McQueen (umamusume)|]]) as well as [[Daitaku Helios (umamusume)|]].

h5. Associated characters

[[Godolphin Barb (Umamusume)|]] - Fellow Goddess/Training AI

title: vega_(street_fighter)
body:
[b]Vega[/b], known as [b]Balrog[/b] in Japan, is one of the bosses of the [[Street Fighter]] series.

He has been in the Street Fighter series ever since his debut as a boss character in [[Street Fighter II (series)|]]. He is a memorable character, not only infamous for his girl-like [[ponytail]] and battle cries, but also for the [[Claw (weapon)|]] he wields, with his unique fighting style. Vega uses his own fighting style of which is a blend of Spanish Ninjutsu and Bullfighting. 

Vega was born to a noble family in Barcelona, [[Spain]]. As he matured, Vega studied [[Bullfighting]], a cultural tradition amongst the nobles. Afterward, he went to Japan and learned Ninjutsu, a style he believed meshed well with his natural grace and agility. Returning home, Vega combined Bullfighting with Ninjutsu and went into an underground cage fighting circuit where quickly became one of the best. Tragedy struck one day when Vega witnessed the murder of his beautiful mother at the hands of his unattractive stepfather. Her murder was punishment for disrespecting him as his stepfather believed. Witnessing this tragic event warped Vega's mind and from then on he lived a double life; a suave nobleman by day and a narcissistic killer by night who enjoys mutilating ugly people to death using a three-pronged wrist-mounted razor-sharp claw. His very first victim was his stepfather.

Vega's brutal fighting skills and remorseless nature impressed the criminal leader known as [[M. Bison]] so much that he came to him personally with an offer to join Shadaloo. Vega accepted M. Bison's offer purely to improve his own aesthetic senses.

title: crow
body:
A large, all-black passerine [[bird]].

Scientifically, crows are one species of bird in the broader Corvidae family, which includes crows, ravens, rooks, jackdaws, jays, magpies, treepies, choughs, and nutcrackers. On Danbooru, "crow" includes all visually-similar birds in the Corvidae family.

Birds in the Corvidae family range in size from the relatively small pigeon-size jackdaws (Eurasian and Daurian) to the Common Raven of the Holarctic region and Thick-billed Raven of the highlands of Ethiopia. The 40 or so members of Corvus genus occur on all temperate continents (except South America) and several offshore and oceanic islands.

Crow species found in Japan, aside from [[magpie]]s, jays and nutcrackers, include the rook, [[carrion crow]], Eurasian & Daurian jackdaws, the large-billed crow, and the common raven.

[[Touhou]] characters [[Shameimaru Aya]] and [[Himekaidou Hatate]] are crow [[tengu]], while [[Reiuji Utsuho]] is a hell raven youkai.

title: white_castle
body: White Castle is an American regional hamburger restaurant chain with 345 locations across 13 states, with its greatest presence in the Midwest and New York metropolitan area. Founded on September 13, 1921, in Wichita, Kansas, it has been generally credited as the world's first fast-food hamburger chain. It is known for its small, square hamburgers referred to as "sliders". The burgers were initially priced at five cents until 1929 and remained at 10 cents until 1949. In the 1940s, White Castle periodically ran promotional ads in local newspapers which contained coupons offering five burgers for ten cents, takeout only. In 2014, Time named the White Castle slider "The Most Influential Burger of All Time".

title: second_battle_of_el_alamein
body:
[b]The Second Battle of El Alamein[/b] (23 October – 11 November 1942) was a battle of [[World War II]] that took place near the Egyptian railway halt of El Alamein. The [[First Battle of El Alamein]] and the [[Battle of Alam el Halfa]] had prevented the Axis from advancing further into [[Egypt]].

Lieutenant-General [[Bernard Montgomery]] was appointed Commander-in-chief of all allied forces in Africa and led the Eighth Army successful offensive during this battle on which he defeated the Axis forces of [[Erwin Rommel]].

The British [[victory]] was the beginning of the end of the Western Desert Campaign, eliminating the Axis [[Afrika Korps]] threat to Egypt, the Suez Canal and the Middle Eastern and Persian oil fields. The battle revived the morale of the Allies, being the first big success against the Axis since [[Operation Crusader]] in late 1941. The end of the battle coincided with the Allied invasion of French North Africa in [[Operation Torch]] on 8 November, which opened a second front in North Africa.

title: battle_of_leyte_gulf
body:
[b]The Battle of Leyte Gulf[/b] (Japanese: レイテ沖海戦, romanized: [i]Reite Oki Kaisen[/i], lit. [b]Leyte Open Sea Naval Battle[/b]) was the [b]largest naval battle of [[World War II]][/b] and by some criteria [b]the largest naval battle in history[/b], with over 200,000 naval personnel involved. It was fought in waters near the [[Philippines]] islands of Leyte, Samar, and Luzon from 23 to 26 October 1944 between combined [[united_states|American]] and [[Australia]]n forces and the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN), as part of the [b]Allied invasion of Leyte[/b], which aimed to isolate Japan from the colonies that it had occupied in Southeast Asia, a vital source of industrial and oil supplies.

By the time of the battle, [[Japan]] had much fewer capital ships ([[aircraft carrier]]s and [[battleship]]s) left than the Allied forces had total aircraft carriers in the Pacific, which underscored the disparity in force strength at that point in the war. Regardless, the IJN mobilized nearly all of its remaining major naval vessels in an attempt to defeat the Allied invasion, but it was repulsed by the US Navy's Third and Seventh Fleets.

The battle consisted of four main separate engagements (the Battle of the Sibuyan Sea, the Battle of Surigao Strait, the Battle off Cape Engaño, and the Battle off Samar), as well as lesser actions. Allied forces announced the end of organized Japanese resistance on the island at the end of December.

It was also the [b]first battle in which Japanese aircraft carried out organized [[kamikaze pilot]] attacks[/b] (which were deadly effective and sunk many Allied ships), and it was the [b]last naval battle between battleships in history[/b]. The battle ended in a decisive [[victory]] for the Allies. The Japanese Navy suffered heavy losses and never sailed in comparable force thereafter since it was stranded for lack of fuel in its bases for the rest of the war.

title: help:qualifiers
body:
Qualifiers are those things in parenthesis you see at the end of some tags. They serve to make the exact meaning of the tag clear so there is no confusion with other tags.

There are many types of qualifiers.

h4. Artist qualifiers

Many artists go by a short name that can be shared by other artists or characters. So Danbooru qualifies them with another text string that is related to that artist. It may be:

* the artist's website or blog name
* circle name
* The username (often different from their actual displayed name) that artist uses on a site like Pixiv, Twitter, DeviantART, Tinami, etc.
* Nickname

Examples: [[shimo_(depthbomb)]] / [[aile_(crossroads)]] / [[alphonse_(white_datura)]]

See [[howto:artist]] for more info.

h4. Series Qualifiers

For names of characters that can be confused with characters from other series, or with artists. If the series name is long, an abbreviation may be used for the qualifier.

Examples: [[yamada_maya_(infinite_stratos)]] / [[knight_(ragnarok_online)]] / [[araya_(nakaimo)]] / [[angel_(evangelion)]]

h4. Cosplay Qualifier

[[hatsune_miku_(cosplay)]] automatically adds both [[hatsune_miku]] and [[cosplay]] to a post.

h4. Meme Qualifier

[[longcat_(meme)]] automatically adds [[meme]] to a post.

h4. Distinguishing copyrights from characters or objects

[[metroid]] = The game series
[[metroid_(creature)]] = The alien creatures from the series

[[claymore_(series)]] = The manga and anime series.
[[claymore_(sword)]] = A type of sword, which the manga was named after.

h4. Alternate forms of characters

Examples: [[hatsune_miku_(append)]] / [[saigyouji_yuyuko_(living)]]

She has [[long_hair|long]] [[black hair]] with [[tress_ribbon|red tress ribbons]] and [[red eyes]]. Some art makes light on how she essentially looks like a black-haired [[murakumo (kancolle)|Murakumo]] and a pixiv tag is dedicated to how she looks like a tiny [[nagato (kancolle)|Nagato]].

She wears a [[long_sleeves|long-sleeved]] white and blue [[serafuku]] with a yellow scarf on top of the standard Kagerou-class [[pleated skirt]], [[white gloves]] & [[uneven legwear|socks of different lengths]]. She [[dual_wielding|dual wields]] two pistols, one based from a standard 12.7cm twin gun and another is a collection of AA guns. On her back is her rigging. Unlike her sisters, it was made into a style similar to some larger ships' split bow. On her right is the part corresponding to her sisters' rigging with an additional 12.7 gun and a quadruple torpedo launcher attached to it and to her left is a depth charge launcher with another torpedo launcher attached to it.

In her remodel, her scarf has been changed to a rope, her thighhigh gains a stripe, the Standard 12.7cm guns have been replaced by their High-Angle equivalent, a radar has been propped behind her head and finally, camo-textures are added to her uniform.

For her B remodel (which is [i]not[/i] an actual second remodel), she is essentially the same as in her remodel except for her use of long 10cm guns. While she is now significantly more powerful stats-wise, the portrait serves as an art refresher.

h4. Personality
Like Nagato, she has a straightforward and professional personality with great pride in her fighting abilities. Perhaps because of this, she prefers a frontal and aggressive approach in battle rather than to engage in defensive measures.

It is implied in her hourlies that she is the only one in her division with poor culinary skills. At 0700, she said that [[hamakaze (kancolle)|Hamakaze]] told her how to make breakfast for the admiral but it ended in failure. At 1200, Tanikaze made the rice balls they ate at that time. At 1800, she ends up cooking with Urakaze. At 2000, it is revealed Urakaze made custard while Isokaze made grilled fish. The next hourlie implies that Urakaze's dish was better than Isokaze's. This has been exaggerated to the point that, if she and [[hiei (kancolle)|Hiei]] are allowed to cook together, they will produce something that is multiplicatively worse than if the two are allowed to cook separately.

Due to her blunt personality, Isokaze is often depicted by fans as either being oblivious to her poor performance or simply being a narcisstic. Because of this, she is frequently depicted in ecchi/NSFW works as being more seasoned in sexual matters or simply viewing it as another form of competition. Alternatively, others have also depicted her in the more ladylike demeanour.

She is voiced by [[Kawasumi Ayako]], who also voices [[ooyodo (kancolle)|Ooyodo]], [[unryuu (kancolle)|Unryuu]], [[kamikaze (kancolle)|Kamikaze]] and the [[Midway Princess]]. Isokaze, in particular, shares a voice identical to [[Saber (fate)|]], who incidentally has much in common with her.

title: musashi_(battleship)
body:
[b]Musashi[/b] (武蔵), named after the former Japanese province, was one of four planned Yamato-class battleships built for the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN), beginning in the late 1930s. The [[yamato_(battleship)|Yamato-class ships]] were the heaviest and most powerfully armed battleships ever constructed, displacing almost 72,000 long tons (73,000 t) fully loaded and armed with nine 460-millimetre (18.1 in) main guns. Their secondary armament consisted of four 155-millimetre (6.1 in) triple-gun turrets formerly used by the Mogami-class cruisers. They were equipped with six or seven armed floatplanes to conduct reconnaissance.

Commissioned in mid-1942, Musashi was modified to serve as the flagship of the Kidou Butai (Combined Fleet) during [[World War II]], and spent the rest of the year working up. The ship was transferred to Truk, Japan's main wartime naval base in the South Pacific theatre, in early 1943 and sortied several times that year with the fleet in unsuccessful searches for American forces. She was used to transfer forces and equipment between Japan and various occupied islands several times in 1944. Torpedoed in early 1944 by an American submarine, Musashi was forced to return to Japan for repairs, during which the navy greatly augmented her anti-aircraft armament. 

She was present during the [[Battle of the Philippine Sea]] in June, but did not come in contact with American surface forces. During the [[Battle of Leyte Gulf]], Musashi was sunk by an estimated 19 torpedo and 17 bomb hits from American carrier-based aircraft on 24 October 1944. Over half of her crew was rescued. 

Her wreck was located in March 2015 by a team of researchers employed by [[Microsoft]] co-founder Paul Allen.
